# Documentation Sync Policy

Documentation ships in the **same** change as the code/structure it describes.
Stale docs are worse than missing docs.

## Principles

- **Same-PR rule.** If a change alters behavior, structure, or policy, update
  the relevant docs and task records in the same PR.
- **Factual, current state.** Docs describe what *is*, not what is hoped for.
  Label any forward-looking content explicitly.
- **Link integrity.** When files move or are renamed, fix every reference. The
  link checker (`{{CHECKS_DIR}}/check_doc_links.py`) enforces resolvable links;
  prefer repo-root-relative links (`/path/from/root.md`) so they survive being
  mirrored into skill `references/`.

## Per-change-type targets

| When you change… | Also update… |
|------------------|--------------|
| Public API / module surface | the doc(s) describing that surface |
| Repository structure / file moves | `{{CONTRACT_FILE}}` map + any inventory |
| Task / process policy | `tasks/` records and the relevant `{{DOCS_AGENT_DIR}}/*` doc |
| CI / workflow behavior | the workflow files and any CI notes in `{{CONTRACT_FILE}}` |

## Enforced rules

Machine-checkable "change X ⇒ update a doc in Y" rules live in `{{RULES_FILE}}`
and run via `{{CHECKS_DIR}}/check_docs_sync.py`. Add a rule there when a code
area must always travel with a documentation update.
